---
const loops = [
  {
    step: "01",
    title: "Frame the work before the agent starts",
    body:
      "Turn a loose request into context, scope, acceptance criteria, and constraints the agent can actually follow."
  },
  {
    step: "02",
    title: "Choose the professional path before editing",
    body:
      "Give the agent the repo map, the active contracts, the quality bar, the relevant docs, and the operational commands before it edits."
  },
  {
    step: "03",
    title: "Verify against the promise and the quality bar",
    body:
      "Check behavior, docs, public claims, edge cases, security posture, and workflow impact before treating a change as done."
  },
  {
    step: "04",
    title: "Ship with the server state still visible",
    body:
      "Keep environments, processes, tunnels, publishing, health, and logs close enough to the agent workflow to act on them."
  }
];
---

<section class="section">
  <div class="section-heading">
    <p class="eyebrow">The Agent Loop</p>
    <h2>ShipFlow covers the work around the agent, not only the prompt you send it.</h2>
    <p>
      The useful question is not whether AI can write code. It can. The useful
      question is whether your system can direct, inspect, run, and explain that
      work without rewarding the fastest fragile path.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="card-grid">
    {
      loops.map((loop) => (
        <article class="card loop-card">
          <span>{loop.step}</span>
          <h3>{loop.title}</h3>
          <p>{loop.body}</p>
        </article>
      ))
    }
  </div>
</section>
